###FOT BZIP, GZIP AND TAR DECODE
File Extension                                       Command to Decode / Extract         Command to Encode /Compress
file.gz   (Gzip-compressed file)                       gunzip file.gz                      gzip file.txt
file.bz2  (Bzip2 compressed file)                      bunzip2 file.bz2                    bzip2 file.txt #add -k flag to keep original file cos it deletes
file.tar  (Uncompressed Tar archive)                   tar -xvf archive.tar                tar -cvf file.tar file.txt
file.tar.gz or .tgz (Tar archive compressed with Gzip)     tar -xzvf archive.tar.gz        tar -czvf archive.tar.gz /path/to/folder
.tar.bz2 or .tbz2 (Tar archive compressed with Bzip2)  tar -xjvf archive.tar.bz2           tar -cjvf archive.tar.bz2 /path/to/folder

Key Behavior: 
- Gzip only compresses single files. If you try to gzip a folder, it won't work. When you run gunzip file.gz, 
  it restores the original file and deletes the .gz version.
- Bzip2 uses a different mathematical algorithm than Gzip. It usually achieves better compression (smaller file sizes), 
  but it takes more time and CPU power to encode and decode. Like Gzip, it only works on single files.
- tar does not compress files to make them smaller. Instead, it takes a whole folder hierarchy and "stitches" them together into one single file
  (often called a "tarball").
- The Flag Breakdown: To decode a basic .tar file, you use tar -xvf:
     -x: Extract the files (decode them).
     -v: Verbose (show a list of files on screen as they extract).
     -f: File (tells tar that the very next argument is the filename).
*****COMBINED
Because gunzip and bunzip2 can't compress folders, and tar can't make files smaller, Linux users combine them.
First, tar groups a folder into archive.tar. Then, gzip shrinks it into archive.tar.gz.
When you want to decode these combined files, the tar command is smart enough to handle the decompression and the extraction all
in one step using special "shortcut" flags:
 For .tar.gz (uses the -z flag for gzip): tar -xzvf archive.tar.gz #this -z flag is to compress by tar and encode by gunzip 
 For .tar.bz2 (uses the -j flag for bzip2): tar -xjvf archive.tar.bz2  #this -j flag is to compress by tar and encode by gunzip 
